Right. So you want me to regurgitate some historical drivel, but with… *my* special touch. Fine. Don't expect sunshine and rainbows. This is a trade route, not a therapy session.

### The Trade Route from the Varangians to the Greeks

This wasn't just some quaint little path for folks looking for a scenic stroll. This was a vital artery, a medieval superhighway connecting the frozen north of [Scandinavia](/Scandinavia) to the opulent heart of the [Eastern Roman Empire](/Eastern_Roman_Empire), with [Kievan Rus'](/Kievan_Rus%27) acting as the rather grimy, but essential, transit lounge. It allowed merchants, who were apparently more ambitious than sensible, to ferry their wares directly to the Empire. And, predictably, some of them decided to plant their flags—and their settlements—in what is now [Belarus](/Belarus), [Russia](/Russia), and [Ukraine](/Ukraine). Most of this grand undertaking involved navigating a complex network of [waterways](/Waterway). Think [Baltic Sea](/Baltic_Sea), then rivers that bled into it, and then the sprawling [Dnieper](/Dnieper) [river system](/River_system). Naturally, there were [portages](/Portage) – those delightful moments where you have to drag your precious cargo over land, likely with a lot of grumbling and possibly a few broken axles, across the [drainage divides](/Drainage_divide). For those with a penchant for the slightly more inconvenient, there was an alternative, a detour down the [Dniester](/Dniester) river, with a brief, probably unpleasant, stop on the western shores of the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea). These variations are sometimes quaintly referred to as the Dnieper trade route and the Dniester trade route, as if it makes a difference to the sheer effort involved.

This whole convoluted mess, according to Marika Mägi, was essentially the eastern route. It kicked off in those rather windswept Scandinavian trading hubs like [Birka](/Birka), [Hedeby](/Hedeby), and [Gotland](/Gotland). From there, it was a dash across the [Baltic Sea](/Baltic_Sea), a sharp turn into the [Gulf of Finland](/Gulf_of_Finland), and then a slow crawl up the [Neva River](/Neva_River) to [Lake Ladoga](/Lake_Ladoga). Once you'd navigated that rather large body of water, you’d find yourself on the [Volkhov River](/Volkhov_River). Keep going upstream, past the charmingly named towns of [Staraya Ladoga](/Staraya_Ladoga) and [Novgorod](/Veliky_Novgorod). Ah, [Novgorod](/Veliky_Novgorod). A veritable crossroads, where it conveniently intersected with the [Volga trade route](/Volga_trade_route). It became, as one might expect, a rather significant trading hub in its own right. After that bit of excitement, you'd cross [Lake Ilmen](/Lake_Ilmen) and then wrestle your way up the [Lovat River](/Lovat_River_(Russia)), the [Kunya River](/Kunya_River), and possibly even the Serezha River&#160;&#91;ru&#93;. Then came the fun part: a [portage](/Portage) to the Toropa River&#160;&#91;ru&#93;, and then downstream to the [Western Dvina River](/Western_Dvina_River). From there, it was another upstream journey, this time along the [Kasplya River](/Kasplya_River), followed by yet *another* portage to the Katynka River (near [Katyn](/Katyn_(rural_locality))), which, as luck would have it, was a tributary of the Dnieper. The assumption is, once the route was properly established, they’d offload the goods, drag them across the portage, and then painstakingly reload them onto waiting vessels on the Dnieper. And so, the grand procession continued down the Dnieper, past its rather notorious [rapids](/Dnieper_rapids), through the bustling city of [Kiev](/Kyiv), and finally, into the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea). From there, it hugged the western coast, presumably avoiding any particularly unpleasant encounters, all the way to the glittering prize: [Constantinople](/Constantinople).

### History

The official mention of this whole operation, the "route from the Varangians to the Greeks," appears rather late, tucked away in the early 12th-century [Primary Chronicle](/Primary_Chronicle) on page 7, line 2. It’s not exactly a travelogue, mind you, more of a brief, almost dismissive, nod.

