But the *real* gossip, the actual observations, come from much earlier. [Constantine VII Porphyrogenitus](/Constantine_VII), a Byzantine emperor with an apparent fascination for the details, noted in his book [De Administrando Imperio](De_Administrando_Imperio) that these "Rhos" (which, for the Byzantines, was a catch-all term for Scandinavians and their kin in the region) would descend the Dnieper from places like [Novgorod](/Veliky_Novgorod), [Smolensk](/Smolensk), [Liubech](/Liubech), [Chernigov](/Chernihiv), and [Vyshgorod](/Vyshhorod), eventually congregating in [Kiev](/Kyiv) before making their final push down to the Black Sea in June. It's important to remember that "Varangians" wasn't just a label for "Vikings" as we tend to think of it now; it was a broader designation for anyone from Scandinavia and their associates in the territories that are now [Belarus](/Belarus), [Russia](/Russia), and [Ukraine].

This whole operation probably got rolling in the late 8th and early 9th centuries. The Varangians, bless their adventurous hearts, were out for plunder, sure, but also for [slaves](/Slavery) and anything else that might fetch a decent price. The route really hit its stride from the 10th to the early 11th century, running concurrently with the [Volga trade route](/Volga_trade_route) and the [trade route from the Khazars to the Germans](/Trade_route_from_the_Khazars_to_the_Germans). A busy time for everyone, I suppose.

Constantine VII also sheds some light on the logistics. He mentions that the [Krivichs](/Krivichs) and other tribes under Kiev’s influence would transport these hollowed-out boats, called [monoxyla](/Monoxyla) (which could apparently fit thirty to forty people – cozy), down the rivers to Kiev. There, they'd sell them to the Varangians. These enterprising souls would then refit them, load them with their merchandise, and continue their journey.

### Routes and Places

The Byzantine chronicler wasn't shy about naming names, or at least, their approximations of them. Places like [Smolensk](/Smolensk) (Μιλινισκα), [Liubech](/Liubech) (Τελιουτζα), [Chernihiv](/Chernihiv) (Τζερνιγωγα), [Vyshhorod](/Vyshhorod) (Βουσεγραδε), Vitichev&#160;&#91;pl&#93; (Βιτετζεβη), and, of course, [Kiev](/Kyiv) (Κια[ο]βα) all get a mention. Some of these had Old Norse equivalents. Constantine, bless his thoroughness, quotes some of them: [Novgorod](/Veliky_Novgorod) (Νεμογαρδα) was also known as Hólmgarðr (‘Island Enclosure’) or Nýgarðr (‘New Enclosure’). [Kiev](/Kiev) was apparently Kœnugarðr (‘Boatyard’), or perhaps Σαμβατας, a name Constantin Zuckerman suggests might have Turkic (Khazar) roots, meaning "upper fortress." The [runestone N 62](/Varangian_Runestones) throws another name into the mix: Vitaholmr (‘demarcation islet’). Boris Kleiber thought this referred to Vitichev. Judith Jesch, however, is less convinced, suggesting it might point to [Witland](/Witland) on the eastern side of the [River Vistula](/Vistula), or perhaps [Vindau](/Ventspils) on the coast of [Courland](/Courland). Always a debate, isn't it?

#### Dnieper Route

Navigating the [Dnieper](/Dnieper) was no picnic. The [Varangians](/Varangian) had to [portage](/Portage) their ships around seven formidable [rapids](/Dnieper_Rapids), all while keeping a wary eye out for the ever-present [Pecheneg](/Pecheneg) nomads. These rapids, a rather inconvenient geological feature, started below what is now the city of [Dnipro](/Dnipro), where the river took a sharp turn south. They cascaded over a drop of about 50 meters in just 66 kilometers. It's worth noting that these rapids are now submerged, thanks to the construction of the [DniproHES](/Dnieper_Hydroelectric_Station) dam in 1932. A modern inconvenience for a historical problem.

Below the rapids, there was a particularly treacherous narrow, rocky stretch known as the Ford of Vrar. This is where the Pechenegs were fond of ambushing unsuspecting travelers. After surviving that ordeal, they’d find refuge at [St. George Island](/Khortytsia). Once past this, they'd rig up sails in the [Dnieper estuary](/Berezan_Island) and set sail along the western coast of the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea), their ultimate destination being [Constantinople](/Constantinople) (known to the Slavs as [Tsargrad](/Tsargrad) and to the Old Norse as [Miklagarðr](/Miklagard)).

For those who preferred to avoid the Dnieper rapids altogether, there was the "Zalozny"&#160;&#91;ru; uk&#93; &#91;11&#93; route. This detour took them through the rivers [Samara](/Samara_(Dnieper)), [Vovcha](/Vovcha), and [Kalmius], eventually leading into the [Sea of Azov](/Sea_of_Azov). From there, they’d make a stop at [Tmutarakan] before continuing along the Black Sea coast to Constantinople. A bit more meandering, perhaps, but it avoided the most dangerous parts of the Dnieper.

#### Western Black Sea Shores

These Varangian vessels weren't just for rivers; they plied the Black Sea shores too. Constantine VII mentions stops at Sulina (in the [Danube Delta](/Danube_Delta)), Conopa, and Constantia (locations now in Romania). There's even evidence of their presence at the [Murfatlar Cave Complex](/Murfatlar_Cave_Complex) near Constantia (modern-day Constanţa, Romania). The cave walls bear numerous runic inscriptions, symbols, and even a graffiti depicting a Viking navy. Quite the historical graffiti wall. A runestone from the Sjonhem cemetery in Gotland, dating to the 11th century, even commemorates a merchant named Rodfos. He was en route to Constantinople, only to be killed north of the Danube by the "Blakumenn" (which translates to Vlachs). A grim reminder of the perils.

### Trade Activities

This grand Varangian artery wasn't an isolated phenomenon. It connected to other vital waterways of Eastern Europe. There was the [Pripyat](/Pripyat_River)-[Bug](/Bug_River) waterway, which offered passage to [Western Europe](/Western_Europe). And, of course, the aforementioned [Volga trade route](/Volga_trade_route), a downward journey along the [Volga](/Volga) to the [Caspian Sea](/Caspian_Sea). Another branch snaked along the Dnieper and the Usyazh-Buk River, leading to [Lukoml](/Lukoml) and [Polotsk](/Polotsk).

The cargo itself was a testament to the diverse demands of the time. From the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) came [wine](/Wine), [spices](/Spices), intricate [jewelry](/Jewelry), fine [glass](/Glass), luxurious fabrics, religious [icons](/Icon), and books. [Volhyn] contributed [spinning wheels](/Spinning_wheel) and other such items. [Scandinavia](/Scandinavia) sent over its share of [weapons](/Weapon) and [handicrafts](/Handicraft). Northern Rus' offered the raw materials: timber, fur, honey, and wax. And from the [Baltic tribes](/Baltic_tribes), the highly prized [amber](/Amber).

However, as is the way with history, things change. By the second half of the 11th century, the [Crusades](/Crusades) opened up new, and apparently more profitable, routes from Europe to the East, cutting through the Middle East. Simultaneously, [Rus'](/Kievan_Rus%27) had been strengthening its own commercial ties with Western Europe. Consequently, the trade route from the Varangians to the Greeks began its slow, inevitable decline, its significance gradually waning. For a related military path, one might look at the [Muravsky Trail](/Muravsky_Trail).

### In Popular Culture

It seems this ancient route has a certain romantic appeal, even now. You can hear it in the lyrics of [Turisas](/Turisas)' song "[To Holmgard and Beyond](/To_Holmgard_and_Beyond)", from their 2007 album [The Varangian Way](/The_Varangian_Way):

> "Holmgard and beyond
> That's where the winds will us guide
> For fame and for gold
> Set sail for those lands unknown"

It’s quite the evocative image.

And then there are the books. [Frans Gunnar Bengtsson](/Frans_Gunnar_Bengtsson)'s massive Swedish historical novel [The Long Ships](/The_Long_Ships) (originally *Röde Orm*) dedicates a significant chunk to the adventures of a Swedish ship’s crew, guided by a pilot from [Gotland](/Gotland), as they navigate this route in the late 10th century. [Rosemary Sutcliff](/Rosemary_Sutcliff)'s 1976 novel [Blood Feud](/Blood_Feud_(novel)) plunges us into the 10th century, following a half-[Saxon](/Saxon) orphan who joins a [Viking](/Viking) crew on this very route, eventually finding himself in the [Varangian Guard](/Varangian_Guard) in [Constantinople](/Constantinople). [Henry Treece](/Henry_Treece)'s *Viking Trilogy* also touches upon it. The second book, [The Road to Miklagard](/Viking_Trilogy), details a [Viking](/Viking) voyage through the [Mediterranean](/Mediterranean) to [Constantinople](/Constantinople), where the protagonists are enslaved before eventually returning home. [Stephen R. Lawhead](/Stephen_R._Lawhead)'s novel *Byzantium* features a 9th-century [Irish](/Irish_people) [monk](/Monk) who is taken by Viking raiders from [Scandia](/Scandia) to [Constantinople](/Constantinople) via this route. Even [Prince Valiant](/Prince_Valiant) has his adventures along these waterways, traveling with [Viking longships](/Longship) from Constantinople to Scandinavia, encountering [Patzinaks](/Patzinaks) and [Polotjans](/Cumans) along the way.

The musical landscape also reflects this fascination. Two albums, released in 2007, coincidentally explore fictional journeys down this route: [Rebellion](/Rebellion_(band))’s [Miklagard — The History of the Vikings Volume 2](/Miklagard_%E2%80%94_The_History_of_the_Vikings_Volume_2) and [Turisas](/Turisas)' [The Varangian Way](/The_Varangian_Way). Turisas, in particular, uses Scandinavian names and [Old Norse exonyms](/List_of_Old_Norse_exonyms) for places like [Holmgard](/Veliky_Novgorod) and [Miklagard](/Names_of_Istanbul) to evoke the historical context of their songs, focusing on the Scandinavian journeys eastward. Finally, [Michael Crichton](/Michael_Crichton)'s fictional work [Eaters of the Dead](/Eaters_of_the_Dead), which later became the film [The 13th Warrior](/The_13th_Warrior), uses the initial framework of this trade route to depict a journey from the Middle East all the way to Scandinavia.

It’s a route that, despite its historical significance, seems to have captured the imagination, leaving a trail of stories etched in ink and melody.